dismissalText.commentary: Ian Bell c Mills b O'Brien 43 (41b 5x4 0x6 51m) SR: 104.87

dismissalComment.html: the breakthrough at last, and O'Brien has his maiden scalp. Short, but a touch quicker than England have been used to in recent overs. A steepling top-edge, well pouched in the deep by Kyle Mills. Timely for New Zealand, but a handy innings nonetheless

commentPreTextItems.html: Two to win, one ball remaining. Could you ask for more ... here comes Wright ...

commentTextItems.html: the ball is fired in at his feet, it cannons off his boot with some edge as well into the off side, the batsmen run, a diving underarm throw misses as Mills hurls himself towards the crease ... and he makes it. We have a tie!

commentPostTextItems.html: Well, what a finish. That keeps the series alive and we now go to Christchurch on Saturday with England needing to win to salvage a draw .  It was a day dominated by the bat and for the last third New Zealand always seemed to have enough in the tank to get home. But then we had wickets, controversy and it came down to the last ball.

"We were dead and buried going into the last six," Collingwood admitted. "I gambled on Wrighty and what a fantastic job he did." And some.  You have to say that New Zealand will look on that as an opportunity missed, although Collingwood did say that he had no idea what emotions he should have.

dismissalText.commentary: Jamie How run out (Anderson) 139 (116b 10x4 3x6 187m) SR: 119.82

commentTextItems.html: full toss hit hard to mid-off, Anderson picks up and throws down the bowler's end stumps with the batsman yards short

commentPostTextItems.html: A sad end to a really wonderful innings from How. When he came in we said he was not the man for the situation ... we were utterly wrong.  As for Anderson, his bowling has been poor but his fielding all day has been awesome ...

commentTextItems.html: hit hard to midwicket, Pietersen gathers cleanly and hurls at the bowler's end ... it misses by inches with the batsman nowhere to be seen

commentPreTextItems.html: Now the batsmen have a chat ...

commentTextItems.html: driven very hard to long-on, yet again Vettori takes on the arm and this time he gets home without the third umpire being needed  ... not that he did England any favours last time!

commentPreTextItems.html: Another long chat ... everyone has an opinion and wants to air it. Fielders moving here, there and everywhere ... it's chaos out there!

commentTextItems.html: bottom edge into the ground, it scoots to Broad at short fine leg

commentPreTextItems.html: Now, the gamble has been that this would be sorted before the last over ... but now Collingwood has to make the call ... Mascarenhas or Shah?  Nope ... it's Luke Wright. Knock me sideways ...

commentTextItems.html: full, straight and hit to long-on
a good delivery to finish a poor day with the ball for Anderson, up in the blockhole and a single into the leg side

commentTextItems.html: same shot, right across his stumps, steered right to Sidebottom this time but still the single

commentPreTextItems.html: Anderson moves his third man wider ...

commentTextItems.html: Vettori shimmies to the off and works behind square on the leg, Sidebottom does well to slide and throw at fine leg, Mustard fumbles the return ... had he not, it would have been mighty close ...but it's all academic
not timed, long-on fields one that was aimed into the off side
fuller and only a single to long-on this time
clubbed over long-on
more bottom hand, turned to the right of long-on, Vettori turns for the second without looking at Anderson whose throw is accurate but the batsman makes his ground

commentPostTextItems.html: Hmm .. the third umpire might have got that wrong because Vettori was home but his bat had bounced in the air and so he was actually out ... so out in-house umpire tells us

commentPreTextItems.html: Another delay as Pietersen chats with Sidebottom.

commentTextItems.html: almost a yorker, Vettori does well to drive back to the right of a diving Sidebottom, long-off mops up
wide full toss, hit with oodles of bottom hand to long-on
half volley driven to long-on but with no power

commentPreTextItems.html: A long delay as the field is tinkered with

commentTextItems.html: classic yorker, outside off swinging into the left hander and rips through him

commentPreTextItems.html: Sidebottom up for his last over. 23 off 18 ...

commentTextItems.html: full and outside off stump, guided with an open face to deepish cover
again full and swinging in, driven to long-off

commentPostTextItems.html: Finally Anderson finds his rhythm ... late but better so than never for those who like tight finishes.
